'''Francis de Vries''' ({{IPA|nl|ˈfrɑn.sɪs də ˈvrizə|lang}};<ref>https://www.instagram.com/reel/DO7XCmGCfrr/?igsh=MWkzYWk3ZmFjd2NpYw==</ref> born 28 November 1994) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays for [[A-League Men|A-League]] club [[Auckland FC]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

==Club career==
===Canterbury United===
De Vries played for [[Canterbury United FC|Canterbury United]] in his youth. He played in the team which won the [[New Zealand Youth National League|ASB Premiership Youth League]] in 2011.

===FC Basel===
De Vries was initially scouted to attend the APFA Academy in [[Christchurch]], New Zealand, under the guidance of professional coaches Giovani Fernandes and Jess Ibrom. The academy had a direct relationship with [[Chelsea FC]] as well as a number of professional clubs all around the World including [[FC Basel]] in Switzerland. In 2012, De Vries would sign a six month contract with their Under-18s side.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uslleaguetwo.com/news_article/show/675430 |title=Michigan Bucks' Francis De Vries |website=Uslpdl.com |date= 2 August 2016|access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref>

===Saint Francis University===
Following his release by Basel, de Vries opted to move to the [[United States]] to play [[College soccer in the United States|college soccer]] at [[Saint Francis University (Pennsylvania)|Saint Francis University]], where he played for four years and made 79 appearances, scoring 15 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfuathletics.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=5126 |title=Saint Francis University Red Flash Athletics – Francis De Vries – 2016 |website=Sfuathletics.com |date= |access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref>

While at college, de Vries played with [[Premier Development League]] side [[Michigan Bucks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uslpdl.com/francis-de-vries |title=Francis De Vries |website=Uslpdl.com |date=2017-01-13 |access-date=2017-05-17 |archive-date=4 April 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404044230/http://www.uslpdl.com/francis-de-vries |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Vancouver Whitecaps FC 2===
On 13 January 2017, de Vries was selected in the second round (29th overall) of the [[2017 MLS SuperDraft]] by [[Vancouver Whitecaps FC]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/post/2017/01/13/whitecaps-fc-select-francis-de-vries-second-round-2017-mls-superdraft |title=Whitecaps FC select Francis de Vries in the second round of the 2017 MLS SuperDraft &#124; Vancouver Whitecaps FC |website=Whitecapsfc.com |date=1994-11-28 |access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref> He signed to [[Whitecaps FC 2]] on 16 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.whitecapsfc.com/wfc2/post/2017/03/15/whitecaps-fc-sign-centre-back-francis-de-vries-wfc2-roster |title=Whitecaps FC sign centre back Francis De Vries to WFC2 roster &#124; Vancouver Whitecaps FC |website=Whitecapsfc.com |date=2017-03-17 |access-date=2017-05-17}}</ref>

===Canterbury United FC===
On 24 November 2017, de Vries signed with [[New Zealand Football Championship|ISPS Handa Premiership]] side [[Canterbury United FC]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/98876859/new-zealand-defender-francis-de-vries-chases-pro-dream |title=Canterbury United sign promising defender Francis De Vries as pro football career stalls |website=stuff.co.nz |date=2017-11-24 |access-date=2017-11-27}}</ref>

===Nyköpings BIS===
On 21 July 2018, de Vries signed with [[Nyköpings BIS]] in the [[Swedish Football Division 1|Division 1 Norra]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svenskalag.se/bissarnaherr/nyheter/1181327/francis-de-vries-klar-for-nykoping/ |title=Francis de Vries klar för Nyköping|website=svenskalag.se |date=2018-07-21 |access-date=2018-07-22}}</ref>

===IFK Värnamo===
In January 2019, de Vries joined [[Division 1 Södra]] side [[IFK Värnamo]]. He played a key part in his club's consecutive promotions to the [[Allsvenskan]] and appeared in their first eleven top-flight games, but suffered a severe [[anterior cruciate ligament]] injury in July 2022 and returned to New Zealand to recover.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/126862484/is-it-real-francis-de-vries-helps-tiny-swedish-club-reach-topflight-status |title='Is it real?': Francis de Vries helps tiny Swedish club reach top-flight status |publisher=Stuff |date=13 November 2021 |access-date=12 December 2021}}</ref>

===Eastern Suburbs===
In 2023 following his return from injury, de Vries signed with Semi-Professional side [[Eastern Suburbs AFC|Eastern Suburbs]] in the [[Northern League (New Zealand)|New Zealand Northern League]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Eastern Suburbs land three big signings ahead of new Northern League season | date=14 March 2023 | url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2023/03/14/eastern-suburbs-land-three-big-signings-ahead-of-new-northern-league-season/ }}</ref>

===Auckland FC===
On 30 May 2024, de Vries joined [[Auckland FC]] as one of 4 inaugural sigings.<ref name="30MayAucklandarrivals">{{cite web|url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/auckland-fc-unveil-first-signings-ahead-of-debut-season/|title=Auckland FC unveil first signings ahead of debut season|website=[[Auckland FC]]|date=30 May 2024}}</ref> On 30 November, de Vries scored his first [[A-League Men|A-League]] goal in a 2–0 win over the [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]]. He later won the Members' Player of the Season award for the 2024–25 season.<ref>{{cite web |title=A Knight of Celebration for Auckland FC |url=https://aucklandfc.co.nz/news/a-knight-of-celebration-for-auckland-fc/ |website=Auckland FC |date=30 May 2025 |access-date=22 November 2025}}</ref> De Vries would feature in Auckland FC's first 50 matches, becoming the first player to play 50 matches for the club, before suffering a calf injury which ruled him out for 6 weeks.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rollo|first=Phillip|date=31 March 2026|title=Auckland FC dealt major blow as All Whites defender Francis de Vries ruled out for rest of regular season |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/360958211/francis-de-vries-out-six-weeks-massive-hit-auckland-fc |website=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>

==International career==
Born in New Zealand, de Vries is of Dutch and Swiss descent.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cranford |first=Aaron |date=2 August 2016 |title=Michigan Bucks' Francis De Vries |url=https://www.uslleaguetwo.com/news_article/show/675430-michigan-bucks-francis-de-vries |website=USL League Two}}</ref> On 16 November 2021, de Vries made his international debut for [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]] as a 95th minute substitute in a friendly match against [[Gambia national football team|The Gambia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/109798?newsfeedId=1275622 |title=Three wins in a row for the All Whites after 2–0 victory over The Gambia |publisher=NZ Football |date=17 November 2021 |access-date=12 December 2021}}</ref> De Vries scored his first goal for the [[New Zealand men's national football team|All Whites]] in a World Cup qualifying match against [[Samoa national football team|Samoa]], an 8–0 win at [[Go Media Stadium]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Francis de Vries scores first All Whites goal as New Zealand thrash Samoa 8–0 |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/147612?newsfeedId=1275608 |website=New Zealand Football |date=18 November 2024 |access-date=22 November 2025}}</ref>

On 14 May 2026, de Vries was named in the 26-man New Zealand squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=New Zealand Squad Named for FIFA World Cup 2026 |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/nzfootball |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=www.nzfootball.co.nz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Powell |first=Alex |title=Wood, Smith make history as All Whites name 26-man World Cup squad |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/football-world-cup/fifa-world-cup-live-updates-all-whites-name-squad-for-2026-tournament/VO65EA66YRHJTDPOMT4V2RYVZ4/ |access-date=2026-05-17 |website=NZ Herald |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

